1
00:01:40,092 --> 00:01:41,843
My name is Kathy H.

2
00:01:43,137 --> 00:01:45,013
I'm 28 years old.

3
00:01:48,309 --> 00:01:50,727
I've been a carer
for nine years.

4
00:01:58,109 --> 00:02:00,068
And I'm good at my job.

5
00:02:00,904 --> 00:02:03,697
My patients always do
better than expected

6
00:02:03,781 --> 00:02:05,782
and are hardly ever
classified as agitated,

7
00:02:07,285 --> 00:02:10,078
even if they're
about to make a donation.

8
00:02:13,082 --> 00:02:15,042
I'm not trying to boast,

9
00:02:15,126 --> 00:02:18,253
but I feel a great sense
of pride in what we do.

10
00:02:19,255 --> 00:02:21,965
Carers and donors
have achieved so much.

11
00:02:25,345 --> 00:02:27,595
That said,
we aren't machines.

12
00:02:31,141 --> 00:02:33,351
In the end,
it wears you down.

13
00:02:35,145 --> 00:02:39,607
I suppose that's why I now spend
most of my time not looking forwards

14
00:02:39,691 --> 00:02:41,859
but looking back,

15
00:02:41,944 --> 00:02:45,154
to The Cottages and Hailsham,

16
00:02:45,906 --> 00:02:47,657
and what happened to us there.

17
00:02:49,159 --> 00:02:50,576
Me,

18
00:02:51,912 --> 00:02:53,829
Tommy,

19
00:02:54,498 --> 00:02:56,749
and Ruth.

20
00:03:05,800 --> 00:03:11,388
When we are
scattered afar and asunder

21
00:03:11,472 --> 00:03:16,226
Parted are those
who are singing today

22
00:03:16,644 --> 00:03:21,815
When we look back
and forgetfully wonder

23
00:03:22,066 --> 00:03:26,861
What we were like
in our learning and play

24
00:03:27,488 --> 00:03:32,491
Oh, the great days
will bring distance enchanted

25
00:03:32,856 --> 00:03:37,579
Days of fresh air in
the rain and the sun

26
00:03:37,831 --> 00:03:42,876
How we rejoiced as we
struggled and panted

27
00:03:43,044 --> 00:03:49,883
Echoes of dreamland,
Hailsham lives on

28
00:03:56,808 --> 00:03:58,434
Good morning, students.

29
00:03:58,518 --> 00:04:01,395
Good morning, Miss Emily.

30
00:04:02,521 --> 00:04:06,649
It has come to my attention that three
burned cigarettes were discovered,

31
00:04:07,026 --> 00:04:10,111
hidden behind a pot
in the flower garden.

32
00:04:12,406 --> 00:04:14,574
I know that on occasion
students have seen

33
00:04:14,658 --> 00:04:18,453
some of the caretakers and
deliverymen smoking cigarettes,

34
00:04:18,537 --> 00:04:22,999
but I must emphasize, once
again, that it is much, much worse

35
00:04:23,083 --> 00:04:26,586
for a student of Hailsham to
smoke cigarettes than anyone else.

36
00:04:28,964 --> 00:04:32,341
Students of Hailsham
are special.

37
00:04:34,260 --> 00:04:38,430
Keeping yourselves well, keeping
yourselves healthy inside,

38
00:04:38,514 --> 00:04:40,682
is of paramount importance.

39
00:04:41,017 --> 00:04:42,976
Have I made myself clear?

40
00:04:43,061 --> 00:04:45,187
Yes, Miss Emily.

41
00:04:47,982 --> 00:04:51,443
I think, one day,
I'd like five horses.

42
00:04:52,487 --> 00:04:57,199
I don't know all their names,
but I know I'd like five horses.

43
00:04:57,325 --> 00:04:59,034
The best
would be Thunder.

44
00:04:59,118 --> 00:05:02,287
He'd be dangerous to ride,
so you can't ride him.

45
00:05:03,372 --> 00:05:05,456
You can ride

46
00:05:06,416 --> 00:05:08,042
Bramble.

47
00:05:08,794 --> 00:05:11,879
Just so long as you don't
use your crop on him.

48
00:05:13,507 --> 00:05:15,549
That's pretty.

49
00:05:15,634 --> 00:05:17,051
You have it.

50
00:05:19,721 --> 00:05:22,640
Look. Who's that
with Miss Emily?

51
00:05:24,142 --> 00:05:26,310
Do you think
it's the new guardian?

52
00:05:26,394 --> 00:05:27,561
Miss Lucy.

53
00:05:29,106 --> 00:05:31,023
I think it must be.

54
00:05:31,108 --> 00:05:33,734
We haven't had
a new guardian for ages.

55
00:05:46,163 --> 00:05:48,832
Arthur! Arthur!

56
00:05:52,753 --> 00:05:54,254
Catch it, Tommy.

57
00:06:16,985 --> 00:06:19,570
Why didn't Tommy
get the ball?

58
00:06:21,322 --> 00:06:22,948
Excuse me, Miss Lucy?

59
00:06:23,366 --> 00:06:25,617
Why didn't Tommy
get the ball?

60
00:06:26,452 --> 00:06:27,661
When it bounced
over the fence,

61
00:06:27,745 --> 00:06:29,121
it couldn't have
been far from him.

62
00:06:29,789 --> 00:06:32,166
The fence is the boundary
of the Hailsham grounds.

63
00:06:32,292 --> 00:06:34,960
We don't go outside
the boundary, Miss Lucy.

64
00:06:35,211 --> 00:06:36,962
It's too dangerous.

65
00:06:37,422 --> 00:06:38,881
Dangerous?

66
00:06:38,965 --> 00:06:41,591
There was once a boy who
had a big row with all his friends

67
00:06:41,675 --> 00:06:44,051
and then ran off
beyond the boundary.

68
00:06:44,136 --> 00:06:48,347
They found him, two days later,
in the woods. Tied to a tree.

69
00:06:48,891 --> 00:06:50,474
With his hands
and feet cut off.

70
00:06:51,268 --> 00:06:52,518
Dead.

71
00:06:53,312 --> 00:06:55,271
And there was the girl
who climbed over the fence,

72
00:06:55,355 --> 00:06:56,689
by the front gate.

73
00:06:56,773 --> 00:07:00,026
And when she tried to get
back, she wasn't allowed.

74
00:07:00,319 --> 00:07:02,945
And then she starved.
Out there.

75
00:07:03,655 --> 00:07:05,406
Right by the gates.

76
00:07:08,160 --> 00:07:09,327
Who told you
these stories?

77
00:07:09,870 --> 00:07:11,912
Everybody knows them.

78
00:07:12,163 --> 00:07:13,830
And how do you know
they're true?

79
00:07:14,165 --> 00:07:15,165
Of course
they're true.

80
00:07:15,750 --> 00:07:18,543
Who'd make up stories
as horrible as that?

81
00:07:45,278 --> 00:07:48,072
Tommy, what are you doing?

82
00:07:48,365 --> 00:07:50,491
What is it, exactly?

83
00:07:50,575 --> 00:07:53,369
I think it must be a dog.
Is it a dog, Tommy?

84
00:07:53,745 --> 00:07:56,288
It can't be a dog.
Its eyes are too small.

85
00:07:56,498 --> 00:07:58,874
I think it must be
a kind of rat.

86
00:07:58,959 --> 00:08:00,751
Yes, that's it.
Tommy's drawn a rat.

87
00:08:00,835 --> 00:08:01,919
It's not finished yet.

88
00:08:02,003 --> 00:08:04,004
That's right. You haven't
finished the whiskers.

89
00:08:04,089 --> 00:08:06,048
Do you think Tommy's rat will
be selected for The Gallery?

90
00:08:06,132 --> 00:08:07,675
It's not a rat.

91
00:08:10,428 --> 00:08:12,054
It's an elephant.

92
00:08:12,180 --> 00:08:14,055
Children,
back to work.

93
00:08:44,169 --> 00:08:47,296
He's got his shirt on.
His favorite polo shirt.

94
00:08:48,548 --> 00:08:50,924
He really doesn't
suspect a thing.

95
00:08:52,927 --> 00:08:55,220
Looks like no one
wants you, Tommy.

96
00:09:06,524 --> 00:09:08,358
What's he doing?

97
00:09:08,484 --> 00:09:09,860
It's his own fault.

98
00:09:09,944 --> 00:09:13,405
If he learnt to keep his cool,
they'd leave him alone.

99
00:09:13,573 --> 00:09:15,532
I hate you!
I hate you all!

100
00:09:15,616 --> 00:09:16,824
Kath... No, don't!

101
00:09:27,961 --> 00:09:29,754
You shouldn't have...

102
00:09:51,984 --> 00:09:53,818
Kathy H.

103
00:10:06,999 --> 00:10:08,666
What's this from?

104
00:10:09,335 --> 00:10:11,002
I don't remember.

105
00:10:11,170 --> 00:10:13,046
Doctor?

106
00:10:20,345 --> 00:10:22,513
It's nothing.
Just a bruise.

107
00:10:29,104 --> 00:10:30,813
Hello.

108
00:10:31,314 --> 00:10:33,357
Kathy. Kathy H.

109
00:10:34,109 --> 00:10:36,527
Of course. Kathy H.

110
00:10:37,195 --> 00:10:38,737
Come in.

111
00:10:44,744 --> 00:10:46,286
So what can
I do for you?

112
00:10:47,705 --> 00:10:49,164
Well,

113
00:10:49,999 --> 00:10:53,042
I was wondering
what you said to Tommy.

114
00:10:54,169 --> 00:10:56,170
Out on the
playing fields.

115
00:10:56,255 --> 00:10:58,256
I see. Oh.

116
00:10:59,174 --> 00:11:00,842
So what did I say?

117
00:11:03,387 --> 00:11:05,763
I believe I was trying
to calm him down.

118
00:11:05,848 --> 00:11:07,723
Because he seemed upset.

119
00:11:08,225 --> 00:11:11,811
He explained he was often
teased about sport and art,

120
00:11:11,895 --> 00:11:15,231
so I told him he shouldn't
get upset about these things.

121
00:11:15,649 --> 00:11:19,277
The other children are only
teasing him to get a reaction.

122
00:11:21,363 --> 00:11:24,072
And if it happens that he's not
particularly good at sport or art,

123
00:11:24,157 --> 00:11:26,199
well, that doesn't matter.

124
00:11:26,993 --> 00:11:28,869
It's not so important.

125
00:11:34,584 --> 00:11:36,084
Thank you.

126
00:11:58,815 --> 00:12:00,274
Kathy.

127
00:12:03,278 --> 00:12:04,695
Aren't you sitting
with the girls?

128
00:12:04,779 --> 00:12:05,779
Well, I just checked

129
00:12:06,239 --> 00:12:08,491
and I'm pretty sure I'm
not sitting with the girls.

130
00:12:08,575 --> 00:12:09,825
I'm sitting with you.

131
00:12:12,120 --> 00:12:13,662
I wanted to say

132
00:12:15,916 --> 00:12:17,583
I'm sorry.

133
00:12:18,960 --> 00:12:20,961
I didn't mean
to hit you.

134
00:12:22,130 --> 00:12:25,716
I mean, I wouldn't
want to hit any girl.

135
00:12:28,511 --> 00:12:30,178
But particularly
not you.

136
00:12:31,639 --> 00:12:34,432
Well, it was an accident, that's all.

137
00:12:36,644 --> 00:12:39,229
Tommy,
finish those vegetables.

138
00:12:56,664 --> 00:12:59,081
I'm not gonna get angry
like that anymore.

139
00:12:59,165 --> 00:13:02,960
Because of what Miss Lucy
told you, about being creative?

140
00:13:03,044 --> 00:13:04,628
How do you know
about that?

141
00:13:04,712 --> 00:13:05,754
I'm nosey.

142
00:13:09,175 --> 00:13:13,387
She can't actually mean that being
creative isn't important, can she?

143
00:13:13,555 --> 00:13:15,764
I mean, what about
The Gallery?

144
00:13:15,848 --> 00:13:17,849
If being creative
isn't important,

145
00:13:17,934 --> 00:13:19,935
then why have
a gallery at all?

146
00:13:22,730 --> 00:13:24,189
I don't know.

147
00:13:29,194 --> 00:13:32,697
...by arching her back, or
perhaps with the aid of a pillow,

148
00:13:33,615 --> 00:13:35,616
the woman can
arrange herself...

149
00:13:51,133 --> 00:13:53,801
Smile

150
00:14:07,982 --> 00:14:09,399
Good morning, ma'am.

151
00:14:09,483 --> 00:14:10,650
Good morning.

152
00:14:10,735 --> 00:14:12,235
Can I help you?

153
00:14:12,320 --> 00:14:15,238
I wanted one tea, with
milk and sugar in it.

154
00:14:15,990 --> 00:14:18,533
One tea. Right.

155
00:14:25,041 --> 00:14:26,583
Tommy.

156
00:14:26,667 --> 00:14:29,252
Oh! One tea with milk
and sugar in it, please.

157
00:14:29,587 --> 00:14:31,588
No, Tommy.

158
00:14:34,174 --> 00:14:36,383
I want to hear
your own order.

159
00:14:36,468 --> 00:14:38,135
Don't simply repeat
the one you've just heard.

160
00:14:38,928 --> 00:14:41,764
What other drinks
do they serve in cafes?

161
00:14:41,848 --> 00:14:43,182
Water.

162
00:14:46,353 --> 00:14:48,437
Coffee.

163
00:14:50,315 --> 00:14:51,607
So, then.

164
00:14:52,484 --> 00:14:53,776
So, then,

165
00:14:54,944 --> 00:14:57,613
one coffee, please, with
milk and sugar in it.

166
00:15:03,494 --> 00:15:04,827
Thank you.

167
00:15:13,837 --> 00:15:15,797
I think Laura likes Arthur.

168
00:15:16,632 --> 00:15:19,258
All the girls
like Arthur, don't they?

169
00:15:20,135 --> 00:15:21,636
Maybe.

170
00:15:23,138 --> 00:15:24,555
I'm not sure you do.

171
00:15:25,933 --> 00:15:28,059
He's not my type.

172
00:15:28,143 --> 00:15:31,396
I think Laura and Arthur will be
the first in our year to have sex

173
00:15:31,480 --> 00:15:34,940
because, if Arthur wants to,
Laura wouldn't stop him.

174
00:15:35,650 --> 00:15:37,818
I'm sure you're right.

175
00:15:42,156 --> 00:15:43,615
Tommy's changed.

176
00:15:44,617 --> 00:15:46,034
Changed how?

177
00:15:47,328 --> 00:15:48,829
Just changed.

178
00:15:49,997 --> 00:15:51,373
That's all.

179
00:16:21,778 --> 00:16:24,363
What about this
one by Madeleine Kane?

180
00:16:24,740 --> 00:16:28,033
I think it shows more
than technical ability.

181
00:16:28,201 --> 00:16:30,745
It gives a real insight
into the child.

182
00:16:30,871 --> 00:16:33,914
Which is precisely what
Marie-Claude wants for The Gallery.

183
00:16:33,999 --> 00:16:35,791
Yes, I agree.

184
00:16:39,545 --> 00:16:40,628
Mmm.

185
00:16:41,172 --> 00:16:43,047
Put these
two together.

186
00:16:44,133 --> 00:16:45,759
Madame is coming.

187
00:17:36,392 --> 00:17:38,101
Good morning, students.

188
00:17:38,228 --> 00:17:41,229
Good morning, Miss Emily.

189
00:17:42,606 --> 00:17:45,316
There are several
points of order today.

190
00:17:45,400 --> 00:17:49,153
The first is that our good friend,
Madame Marie-Claude, is visiting us.

191
00:17:49,321 --> 00:17:53,533
She will, as usual, be carefully
inspecting your artwork and poetry

192
00:17:53,700 --> 00:17:57,662
and selecting the very best pieces
for inclusion in her Gallery.

193
00:17:58,080 --> 00:18:00,540
We will, of course,
extend to her every courtesy

194
00:18:00,624 --> 00:18:03,292
and make her feel
most welcome.

195
00:18:03,627 --> 00:18:07,213
Second point of order, a piece
of good news for all students

196
00:18:07,297 --> 00:18:10,174
who have been diligent
in collecting tokens.

197
00:18:10,551 --> 00:18:13,385
After studies tomorrow,
there will be a sale.

198
00:18:14,595 --> 00:18:16,972
The delivery
will arrive in the morning,

199
00:18:17,098 --> 00:18:19,432
and I was assured
by the van driver

200
00:18:19,517 --> 00:18:22,769
that the boxes will
contain a bumper crop.

201
00:19:12,527 --> 00:19:14,653
Is it really
a bumper crop?

202
00:19:16,030 --> 00:19:19,449
I should say so. Yeah,
sweetheart. It's a bumper crop.

203
00:20:24,262 --> 00:20:25,638
Hey.

204
00:20:26,848 --> 00:20:28,516
Aren't you buying?

205
00:20:28,892 --> 00:20:32,353
If you've already spent all your
tokens, you can have some of mine.

206
00:20:32,604 --> 00:20:36,190
I have tokens. I was just gonna
wait till the rush died down.

207
00:20:36,274 --> 00:20:39,026
I'm sure there'll be
something good left.

208
00:20:40,153 --> 00:20:42,113
What's the matter, Kath?

209
00:20:45,951 --> 00:20:47,493
Well, anyway,
it doesn't matter

210
00:20:47,577 --> 00:20:50,120
if you can't find
anything in the sale

211
00:20:50,204 --> 00:20:53,832
because I already
found you something.

212
00:20:56,544 --> 00:20:58,003
A music tape.

213
00:20:58,087 --> 00:21:01,715
I don't know much about it,
if it's much good or anything.

214
00:21:05,928 --> 00:21:07,387
Thank you.

215
00:21:13,144 --> 00:21:15,145
* Darling *

216
00:21:17,982 --> 00:21:28,824
* Hold me *

217
00:21:28,908 --> 00:21:30,492
* And never *

218
00:21:31,536 --> 00:21:35,330
* Never *

219
00:21:35,999 --> 00:21:39,626
* Let me go *

220
00:21:48,970 --> 00:21:51,221
* Darling *

221
00:21:53,348 --> 00:22:04,609
* Kiss me *

222
00:22:04,693 --> 00:22:06,569
* And never *

223
00:22:07,071 --> 00:22:11,199
* Never *

224
00:22:11,658 --> 00:22:16,370
* Let me go *

225
00:22:47,485 --> 00:22:49,319
The problem is

226
00:22:50,446 --> 00:22:53,698
you've been told
and not told.

227
00:22:54,534 --> 00:22:57,034
That's what I've seen
while I've been here.

228
00:22:58,370 --> 00:23:00,287
You've been told

229
00:23:00,580 --> 00:23:03,207
but none of you
really understand.

230
00:23:04,209 --> 00:23:08,337
So I've decided I'll talk to you
in a way that you will understand.

231
00:23:12,008 --> 00:23:14,301
Do you know what happens to
children when they grow up?

232
00:23:17,055 --> 00:23:20,766
No, you don't,
because nobody knows.

233
00:23:23,103 --> 00:23:25,646
They might grow up
to become actors,

234
00:23:26,648 --> 00:23:28,606
move to America.

235
00:23:30,359 --> 00:23:32,861
Or they might work
in supermarkets.

236
00:23:33,529 --> 00:23:35,280
Or teach in schools.

237
00:23:36,365 --> 00:23:41,202
They might become sportsmen or bus
conductors or racing car drivers.

238
00:23:41,453 --> 00:23:43,872
They might do
almost anything.

239
00:23:46,208 --> 00:23:48,168
But with you
we do know.

240
00:23:51,297 --> 00:23:53,590
None of you
will go to America.

241
00:23:55,384 --> 00:23:58,344
None of you will work
in supermarkets.

242
00:24:00,597 --> 00:24:02,890
None of you will do
anything except live the life

243
00:24:02,974 --> 00:24:05,184
that has already
been set out for you.

244
00:24:07,812 --> 00:24:09,897
You will
become adults,

245
00:24:11,649 --> 00:24:13,317
but only briefly.

246
00:24:16,779 --> 00:24:18,488
Before you are old,

247
00:24:20,074 --> 00:24:22,409
before you are
even middle-aged,

248
00:24:22,827 --> 00:24:26,163
you will start to donate
your vital organs.

249
00:24:28,666 --> 00:24:31,167
That's what you were
created to do.

250
00:24:33,670 --> 00:24:38,174
And sometime around your
third or fourth donation,

251
00:24:39,259 --> 00:24:42,011
your short life
will be complete.

252
00:24:43,764 --> 00:24:48,100
You have to know who
you are and what you are.

253
00:24:49,061 --> 00:24:52,230
It's the only way
you'll lead decent lives.

254
00:25:43,488 --> 00:25:46,657
There will be only one
announcement this morning,

255
00:25:47,909 --> 00:25:49,451
which is that Miss Lucy,

256
00:25:49,536 --> 00:25:51,954
who was guardian
to the fourth-year students,

257
00:25:52,330 --> 00:25:54,707
is no longer
working at Hailsham.

258
00:25:58,628 --> 00:26:01,505
A replacement will be found
for her, and in the meantime

259
00:26:01,589 --> 00:26:05,591
her classes will be divided
between Miss Geraldine and myself.

260
00:26:07,720 --> 00:26:10,263
It is hard, is it not,

